`frozensetlist.__hash__` currently uses Python's built-in `Set._hash` implementation: https://github.com/mlenzen/collections-extended/blob/68e6895/collections_extended/setlists.py#L535-L539:
```python
class frozensetlist(_basesetlist, Hashable):
	"""An immutable (hashable) setlist."""

	def __hash__(self):
		return Set._hash(self)
```
But this is order-insensitive, so currently `hash(frozensetlist((1, 2))) == hash(frozensetlist((2, 1)))`, which conflicts with the fact that `frozensetlist((1, 2)) != frozensetlist((2, 1))`. Objects which compare unequal should have different hash values whenever possible. Otherwise, when multiple such objects are present in the same set or dict, hash collisions result, and therefore performance of operations such as `__contains__` and `__getitem__` suffers.

For comparison, `hash(tuple((1, 2))) != hash(tuple((2, 1)))`.

https://github.com/dmlc/mxnet/blob/master/src/operator/roi_pooling.cc#L187
```cpp
            for (int ph = phstart; ph < phend; ++ph) {
              for (int pw = pwstart; pw < pwend; ++pw) {
                const int pooled_index = ph * pooled_width_ + pw;
                if (static_cast<int>(offset_argmax_data[pooled_index]) == h * width_ + w) {
                  gradient += offset_top_diff[pooled_index];
                }
              }
            }
```
```phend``` is always equal to ```phstart+1``` , so it can be replaced by:
```cpp
            const int pooled_index = phstart * pooled_width_ + pwstart;
            if (static_cast<int>(offset_argmax_data[pooled_index]) == h * width_ + w) {
              gradient += offset_top_diff[pooled_index];
            }
```
